{{otheruses}} [[File:Joshua Reynolds – Omai of the Friendly Isles.jpg|thumb|upright|''Omai of the Friendly Isles'' by Sir [[Joshua Reynolds]], c.1774]] [[File:Omai (Mai), Sir Joseph Banks and Daniel Charles Solander by William Parry.jpg|thumb|upright|[[William Parry (artist)|William Parry]]'s painting ''Sir [[Joseph Banks]] with Omai and Dr. [[Daniel Solander]]'', circa 1775-76]] [[File:Joshua Reynolds - Portrait of Omai.jpg|thumb|upright|Sir [[Joshua Reynolds]], ''[[Portrait of Omai]], a South Sea Islander who travelled to England with the second expedition of captain Cook'', 1776]]
'''Mai''' (c.1751-1780), mistakenly known as '''Omai''' in Britain, was a young [[Ra'iatea]]n man who became the second [[Pacific Islander]] to visit Europe, after Ahu-toru who was brought to Paris by [[Louis Antoine de Bougainville|Bougainville]] in 1768.
== Life == Ma'i described himself as a ''hoa'', chiefly attendant, the son of a Ra'iatea landowner. His father was killed by Puni's [[Bora Bora|Borabora]] warriors. Fleeing to Tahiti, Ma'i was wounded in the encounter with the ''[[HMS Dolphin (1751)|Dolphin]]'' in 1767. Ma'i then became an apprentice to a priest. Returning to Ra'iatea, he was captured and taken to Borabora. Narrowly escaping death there, he escaped to Huahine.<ref name="Anne">{{cite book|last1=Salmond|first1=Anne|title=Aphrodite's Island|date=2010|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=9780520261143|pages=283-284,389-402}}</ref>
Omai met [[Samuel Wallis]] in 1767 and Captain [[James Cook]] in 1769 in [[Tahiti]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Quanchi | first = Max|authorlink=| year = 2005 | title = Historical Dictionary of the Discovery and Exploration of the Pacific Islands | publisher = The Scarecrow Press | location = |page=200| isbn = 0810853957}}</ref> In August 1773 he embarked from [[Huahine]] on the British ship {{HMS|Adventure| 1771|6}}, commanded by Commander [[Tobias Furneaux]], which had previously touched at Tahiti as part of [[James Cook]]'s [[Second voyage of James Cook|second voyage of discovery]] in the Pacific. Omai travelled to Europe on ''Adventure'', arriving at [[London]] in October 1774 where he was introduced into British society by the naturalist Sir [[Joseph Banks]] (whom he had also met during Cook's first voyage).<ref>{{Citation | last = Salmond | first = Anne | author-link = Anne Salmond | title = The Trial of the Cannibal Dog | place = New Haven, CT | publisher = Yale University Press | year = 2003 | url = https://yalebooks.yale.edu/book/9780300100921/trial-cannibal-dog | isbn = 978-0-300-10092-1 | page = 3 }}</ref>
During his two-year stay in England, Omai became much admired within London high society. Renowned for his charm, quick wit and exotic good looks, he quickly became a favourite of the aristocratic elite.<ref name="Holmes">Holmes, R. (2009) ''The Age of Wonder: How the Romantic Generation Discovered the Beauty and Terror of Science'' (London: Harper Press) p. 50</ref> Banks regularly invited Omai to dine with the [[Royal Society]] and arranged meetings with notable celebrities of the time, including [[John Montagu, 4th Earl of Sandwich|Lord Sandwich]], [[Dr Samuel Johnson]], [[Frances Burney]], and [[Anna Seward]], among others.<ref name="Holmes" /> [[Richard Holmes (biographer)|Richard Holmes]] remarks that Omai's idiosyncratic behaviour and distinctive bow were widely celebrated.<ref name="Holmes" /> Indeed, during one famed meeting with [[King George III]] at [[Kew]], Omai is said to have delivered his bow then grasped the King's hand, declaring, "How do, King Tosh!"<ref>O'Brian, P. (1987) ''Joseph Banks'' (Harvill Press) p. 181</ref>
His portrait was painted by Sir [[Joshua Reynolds]] among others, and his journey to England and subsequent return to Tahiti with Cook on his [[Third voyage of James Cook|third voyage]] in 1776 became the subject of a theatrical production, written and directed by the dramatist [[John O'Keefe (British writer)|John O'Keefe]], entitled ''[[Omai – A Voyage ‘round the World]]'' that was performed during the 1785 Christmas season at London’s [[Royal Opera House|Theatre Royal]] in [[Covent Garden]].
Omai returned to Huahine in August 1777 and was settled with a European-style house, furniture, vineyard and two [[Maori people|Maori]] boys as his servants. During the [[HMS Bounty|Bounty]]'s visit to Tahiti in 1789, [[William Bligh|Captain Bligh]] was told Omai had died about two and a half years after Cook's departure in November 1777.<ref>{{cite press release | title = Temporary Export Bar For 'Outstanding' Reynolds' Portrait Of Omai | publisher = United Kingdom Department for Culture, Media and Sport | date = 17 December 2002 | url = http://www.culture.gov.uk/reference_library/media_releases/2884.aspx | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080727031027/http://www.culture.gov.uk/reference_library/media_releases/2884.aspx | dead-url = yes | archive-date = 27 July 2008 | accessdate = 6 December 2008 }}</ref>
